\cleardoublepage

\section*{\centering{Abstract}}
\setstretch{1.5}
\fontsize{12}{13.5}\selectfont

Coordination between source and sink organs in trees is important to ensure that enough carbon gets assimilated by the source (leaves) and that photosynthates are efficiently used by the plant, either being transported to the sink organs, or kept in the source as energy reserve (carbon allocation). When sink demand is reduced, photosynthetic activity in the leaves and phloem transport rate have been shown to decrease as well, due to feedback mechanisms (Chiou \& Bush, 1998). 
\smallskip

For this experiment, sink demand reduction was obtained by cooling the soil around the roots of saplings down to 4 °C: 12 \textit{Betula pendula} saplings in a greenhouse environment received the cooling treatment, while 8 saplings were left untreated and used as controls. Although it is a part of a larger experiment with a wider scope, the data presented and analyzed here aims at describing the effect of soil temperature on four gas exchange variables: $CO_2$ net assimilation (\textit{A}), water evapotranspiration (\textit{E}), stomatal conductance (\textit{gsw}) and photosynthetic efficiency (\textit{A/$C_i$}). Gas exchange variables were found to be significantly different between control trees and cooled trees for three variables (\textit{A}, \textit{E} and \textit{gsw}), with cooled trees having lower source activity. \textit{A/$C_i$} not being significantly affected suggests a minor role of non-stomatal limitation in the decrease of photosynthetic rate. 
\smallskip 

This thesis also investigates the effect of the cooling treatment on water potential. Soil cooling has been shown to negatively affect root water uptake and water potential (Lintunen et al., 2020). This could be part of the reason why photosynthetic activity decreases with temperature. However, in our experiment water potential values were not significantly affected by soil temperature, and did not significantly impact the gas exchange variables.

