\section{Introduction} \label{sec:intro}

Carbon and water fluxes in plants are tightly coupled: during photosynthesis a lot of water is lost for a small carbon gain. Furthermore, transport of photosynthates also requires water. Finally, growth requires water to create turgor for cell expansion and carbon for building the cell elements. Hence, 
connections and feedbacks between different tissues and organs are important for plants to maintain sufficient carbon assimilation and an efficient utilization of photosynthates, without losing an excessive amount of water. Because leaves and carbon sinks are connected through the phloem and the xylem, changes that start from one tissue can easily be propagated to other tissues in the same tree \citep{Hölttä_et_al._2017}. 
\smallskip

This introduction will explore the connection between source and sink organs through phloem transport and, in particular, how gas exchange variables in the leaves, such as the rate of photosynthesis and stomatal conductance, can be affected by changes in carbon sink activity in the roots. 
\smallskip 

The connection between leaves and roots through xylem transport will also be examined, with the same gas exchange variables being impacted by changes in water potential in the roots \citep{Hölttä_et_al._2017}.  

\subsection{Photosynthesis}

Photosynthesis is the basis of the ecosystem food chain and “the ultimate source of all of humankind’s food and oxygen” \citep{Johnson_M._P._2016}. Oxygenic photosynthesis is a process that allows certain organisms, including plants, to harvest solar energy to synthesize organic carbon compounds, starting from carbon dioxide and water and generating oxygen as well \citep{Arnon_D._I._1971}: 

\begin{equation}
   6H_2O + 6CO_2 + light \rightarrow C_6H_{12}O_6 + 6O_2
    \label{eq:photosynthesis}
\end{equation}

The description of photosynthesis below focused on C3 plants, which are common in temperate and boreal regions and which were studied in this thesis. C4 and CAM plants exhibit some variations compared to C3 due to differences in anatomy and biochemical reactions.
\smallskip

Photosynthesis mostly takes place in the leaves. Figure \ref{fig:leaf} shows the typical anatomy of a leaf. Different cell types in the leaf contribute to the photosynthetic process: 
$CO_2$ entry is controlled by stomata in the lower epidermis, photosynthetic parenchyma (mesophyll) cells contain many chloroplasts and are the principal center of photosynthesis, whereas vascular tissues transport the sap with the necessary compounds into the leaves (xylem), or towards the rest of the plant (phloem) \citep{Mauseth_2006}. 
\smallskip

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/leaf.jpg}
    \caption{Representation of the cross-section of a leaf. A waxy cuticle and an epidermal tissue are present on its upper and lower surface. More internally, the leaf contains two types of mesophyll (palisade parenchyma and spongy parenchyma), which contain chloroplasts, and transport tissues (xylem and phloem) in the vascular bundle. Figure from \citet{Diah_S._Z._M._et_al._2014}.}
    \label{fig:leaf}
\end{figure}

The site of photosynthesis in the cell is the chloroplast, an organelle with two outer membranes and one thylakoid membrane. The thylakoid membrane divides the chloroplast into two spaces: the stroma on the outside and the lumen on the inside. 
\smallskip

In plants, photosynthesis can be divided into two phases: 

\begin{itemize}

\item A first light-dependent phase that happens in the thylakoid membrane. It results in the production of adenosine triphosphate  (ATP) and reduced nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADPH). The energy of light is thus converted into chemical energy.

\item A second metabolic phase that happens in the stroma. Here, ATP (high-energy compound) and NADPH (high reducing power) are used by the enzymes of the Calvin-Benson cycle and $CO_2$ gets reduced and fixed into carbohydrates \citep{Johnson_M._P._2016}. ATP and NADPH provide the 479 kJ that are necessary for photosynthesis to occur, as it is an endergonic process \citep{Antal_et_al._2013}. 

\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{images/chloropl.png}
    \caption{Image of a chloroplast from a leaf of Phleum pratense, taken with an electron microscope. A system of thylakoid membranes divides a space called lumen from the external stroma. Thylakoid membranes are the site of the electron transport chain (light phase of photosynthesis). Figure from \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}.}.
    \label{fig:chlor}
\end{figure}

The first phase of photosynthesis requires pigments, which in plant cells are mainly two molecules with a ring structure, chlorophyll \textit{a} and \textit{b} \citep{Queiroz_et_al._2017}. When chlorophyll absorbs photons at certain wavelengths - mostly the blue (425–450 nm) and red parts (600–700 nm) of the visible spectrum -, it reaches an excited, unstable state {that cannot be maintained for long}. As the excited molecule goes back to its ground state, the extra energy can be disposed of through energy transfer to a neighboring molecule, which in turn becomes excited \citep{Rascio_2017}. This is the process that happens in photosystems I and II, two complexes that can be found in the thylakoid membrane. They are formed by hundreds of pigment molecules that collect and transfer energy to a reaction center, called P680 in photosystem I and P700 in Photosystem II. Two specific chlorophyll molecules in the reaction center behave differently than other pigments in the complex: instead of transferring energy, one of them undergoes oxidation, transferring an electron to the other and thus making a redox chain possible \citep{Johnson_M._P._2016}. 
\smallskip

The redox chain (Figure \ref{fig:light}) involves a series of molecules that are present in the thylakoid membrane, ending with ferredoxin/ NADP+ reductase (FNR). This pathway is unidirectional, as electrons are transferred from stronger reductants to weaker ones \citep{Arnon_D._I._1971}. As a result of the electron chain, NAPD+ is reduced to NADPH, whereas water reduces oxidized P680 back to its former state and is therefore converted to oxygen. The electron chain also causes proton transport across the membrane, with an accumulation of protons in the lumen. This gradient is used by the ATP synthase to generate ATP through phosphorylation (\citep{Hill_R._and_Bendall_F._1960, Johnson_M._P._2016}. 

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/light_phase.png}
    \caption{Electron transport chain in the thylakoid membrane, with photosystem II, cythocrome $b_6f$, photosystem I, ferredoxin and FNR. The proton gradient produced by the pathway is used by ATP synthase (phosphorylation). Image from \citet{Johnson_M._P._2016}.}
    \label{fig:light}
\end{figure}

After the light-dependent reactions, there is a metabolic phase: $CO_2$ is fixed into organic compounds during the Calvin-Benson cycle, which is made up of 13 reactions. Primary $CO_2$ assimilation is catalyzed by the enzyme RuBisCO (ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate carboxylase/ oxygenase), when the sugar ribulose-1,5-bisphosphate undergoes carboxylation. The first three reactions lead to the formation of two molecules of a triose phosphate called glyceraldehyde-3-phosphate (G3P), thanks to the previously produced ATP and NADPH, which provide energy and reducing power. The other ten reactions aim at regenerating RuBP so that it can be used in the next cycle \citep{Biel_K._and_Fomina_I._2015}. In total, the cycle uses 3 molecules of ATP and 2 of NADPH to assimilate one $CO_2$ molecule \citep{Rascio_2017}. 
\smallskip

When three $CO_2$ are fixed into six G3P molecules, five of these molecules become a part of the cycle again, by being regenerated into RuBP; the sixth molecule can follow two different paths. It can exit the chloroplast and be converted into fructose-6P and then, after several reactions, into sucrose, or it can remain in the chloroplast and be converted into starch  (\citep{Johnson_M._P._2016}). 


\begin{figure}[hp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{images/calvin_cycle.jpg}
    \caption{The 13 reactions of the Calvin cycle. Figure from \citet{Sun_et_al._2003}.}
    \label{fig:calvin}
\end{figure}
 

\subsection{Water potential and xylem transport}
Sap (water and minerals) is absorbed by the roots and then travels inside a vascular tissue, the xylem, throughout the root system, the stem and the leaves. In Angiosperms, the xylem is constituted by dead, elongated cells that belong to two different categories, tracheids and vessel elements. Both have lignified secondary walls and are stacked on top of one another, but vessel elements have perforated cross walls, forming a continuous tube \citep{Venturas_M._D._et_al._2017}. 
\smallskip

% xylem image?
The concept of water potential, which is defined as a "measure of the free energy of water per unit volume (J $m^{-3}$)" relative to pure water in reference conditions \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}, is fundamental to explain sap transport inside the plant. Water potential can be described by equation \ref{eq:water}:

\begin{equation}
 \psi_{H_{2}O} = \mu_{H_2O}/V_{H_2O},  
 \label{eq:water}
\end{equation}

where $\mu$ is the chemical potential of water and $V_{H_2O}$ is its molar volume \citep{Rascio_2017}. It is made up of different components, which can be summarized by equation \ref{eq:potential}:

\begin{equation}
    \Psi_{H_2O} = \Psi_s + \Psi_p + \Psi_g
    \label{eq:potential}
\end{equation}

$\Psi_g$ is the gravity component, which has a minor role in small plants. $\Psi_p$ is the hydrostatic pressure: when it is positive, this pressure causes $\Psi_{H_2O}$ to become less negative. Osmotic potential ($\Psi_s$) describes the effect of solutes on $\Psi_{H_2O}$. It becomes more negative as solutes accumulate in a plant cell, causing the water potential to also become more negative. Water moves from higher to lower values  when a water potential gradient ($\Delta\Psi_{H_2O}$) is present \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}. 
\smallskip

The roots can contribute directly to water uptake by generating a $\Delta\Psi_{H_2O}$ between soil and root, which is caused by an osmotic gradient. As ions accumulate in the xylem, $\Psi_{H_2O}$ decreases, allowing water to flow in \citep{Gambetta_G.A._et_al._2017}. 

The main force  that drives sap transport, however, is the water potential gradient ($\Delta\Psi_p$) between leaves and roots, as the cohesion-tension theory claims. According to this theory, water in the xylem behaves like a cohesive, unbroken column that can ascend from roots to leaves because it is driven by evaporation happening inside pores of leaf cell walls. Because of the hydrophilic elements in the cell wall, as the water evaporates, the meniscus becomes more concave. The concavity of the water-air interfaces inside the mesophyll cell walls creates a negative pressure (water potential), which propagates to neighboring areas, creating the driving force necessary to pull water from the soil to the evaporation site \citep{Brown_2013}. Unless a plant is stressed due to excessive transpiration, the transpired water should be entirely replaced by the water absorbed by the roots and then transported inside the xylem \citep{Hölttä_et_al._2017}.

The rate of root water uptake (Q) depends on the water potential gradient between the soil and the xylem, and on root surface area (S) \citep{Gambetta_G.A._et_al._2017}. The concept of hydraulic conductivity (Lp) summarizes the relationship with the following equation:

\begin{equation}
    Lp= Q/\Delta\Psi*S
\label{eq:conductivity}    
\end{equation}

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth]{images/Hydraulic_cond.png}
    \caption{Hydraulic conductivity of a root system. The water flow rate in the root (Q) is controlled by a water potential gradient ($\Delta\Psi$) and by the root surface area (A). Figure from \citet{Gambetta_G.A._et_al._2017}.}
    \label{fig:conductance}
\end{figure}

% bigger water pot gradients --> higher traspiration rate --> closed stomata, higher stress due to water loss 

\subsection{Stomata} \label{sec: stomata}
While the relative water vapor concentration in the mesophyll is greater than its concentration in the atmosphere, due to xylem activity, the opposite is true for $CO_2$ concentration, which is lower in the leaf \citep{Venturas_M._D._et_al._2017}. These concentration gradients control water loss ($H_2O$ evapotranspiration) and $CO_2$ uptake, which are also influenced by another factor, the diffusional resistance. Thus, the transpiration rate can be calculated with the following equation:

\begin{equation}
    Tr = \frac{C_{w leaf} - C_{w air}}{R_{leaf} + R_{air}}
\end{equation}

$C_{w leaf}$ and $C_{w air}$ are the concentrations of water vapor in the leaf and in the air, while $R_{leaf}$ and $R_{air}$  represent the resistance in those same spaces \citep{Rascio_2017}. 
\smallskip

In particular, $R_{leaf}$ is the leaf stomatal resistance to gas diffusion, \textit{i.e.} the resistance associated with the stomatal pores in the epidermis of leaves. Plants transpire and take up $CO_2$ through these apertures, therefore the regulation of their size is essential to make sure the plant does not lose too much water, but still gets enough $CO_2$. Thus, stomatal resistance is controlled by two guard cells that surround the pore. If the water uptake by the roots cannot replace the water loss from the leaves, the stomata have to close in order to avoid a drop on water potential and dehydration \citep{Hölttä_et_al._2017}. The guard cells respond to factors such as temperature and intracellular $CO_2$ concentration by changing their turgor pressure, which leads to the opening or closing of the pores \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}. 

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/Stomata_in_out.png}
    \caption{Water and $CO_2$ uptake through the leaf. The concentration gradients control water loss and $CO_2$ uptake through stomatal apertures \textit{e.g.} vapor content concentration in the leaf is higher than in the atmosphere. Stomata exert physical resistance to the gas diffusion. Figure taken from \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}.}
    \label{fig:leaf_2}
\end{figure}

Stomatal resistance is influenced by temperature. For instance, at mid to high latitudes, an increase in temperature is associated with a higher $\Delta C_w$ between the leaf and the air, and therefore to higher transpiration rates, causing an increase in stomatal resistance \citep{Rascio_2017}. The rate of photosynthesis and stomatal conductance are also interconnected: with high photosynthetic activity, stomatal conductance (the inverse of stomatal resistance) is also high, but an increase in the internal leaf $CO_2$ concentration can cause an increase in stomatal resistance in order to limit water loss \citep{Jarvis_and_Davies_1998}).  


\subsection{The phloem}
\subsubsection{Structure and function}
The phloem is a tissue that allows long-distance transport (translocation) of photosynthates, \textit{i.e.} the product of photosynthesis. Redistribution of water and other compounds is another one of its functions. Photosynthates must be transported from their source, usually mature leaves, to areas of growth that are unable to produce enough assimilates, such as young leaves, fruits, or roots. Storage organs, including roots, tubers and rhizomes, can be both sink, when accumulating nutrients, and source, when providing said nutrients to the rest of the plant during winter or other stress-inducing times \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}. Seeds do the same, transitioning from sink to source when they germinate, so that the resources that they accumulated as starch can be used by the new plant to grow \citep{Rascio_2017}.
\smallskip

In Angiosperms, which are the main object of research on the phloem, xylem and phloem form vascular tissues throughout the entire plant, with the xylem being usually closer to the centre of the stem (or the root), and the phloem being external \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}. The two continuously exchange water. 
\smallskip

The phloem is made up of living cells of different categories, most importantly sieve elements and companion cells. In Angiosperms, sieve elements are cylinder-shaped cells that are stacked on top of each other. \citep{Rascio_2017}. The cross walls separating the cells are perforated by pores (Figure \ref{fig:sieve}), forming sieve plates, to achieve symplastic continuity and a higher hydraulic conductance inside the tube \citep{Knoblauch_and_Peters_2017}. Sieve cells do not possess a nucleus, a cytoskeleton and other essential organelles. In order to survive, each one is associated with one or more companion cells, which provide energy and resources to the sieve cells. Solutes can easily be exchanged between sieve cells and companion cells thanks to the plasmodesmata connecting them. Companion cells also contribute to the transport of photosynthates from mesophyll cells in leaves, where they are produced, to sieve cells. \citep{Rascio_2017}. 

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth, angle=0]{images/sieve.png}
    \caption{Hypocotyl of Cucurbita maxima. Image of a longitudinal section of two sieve tube elements, taken with an electron microscope. The pores of the sieve plate are visible between the two elements. The inset shows sieve plate pores. Image taken from \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}.}
    \label{fig:sieve}
\end{figure}

Phloem sap transports soluble sugars, the most common being sucrose, which varies from 0.3 to 0.9 M in concentration. Other solutes in lower concentrations include amino acids, hormones, proteins and inorganic solutes \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}. 
\smallskip

Long-distance transport in the phloem is usually explained by the pressure-flow hypothesis, formulated by Ernst Münch in the 1920s. (Figure \ref{fig:munch}). The hypothesis states that the loading of photosynthates into the phloem at the source causes a low osmotic potential ($\Psi_s$), which in turn causes a more negative water potential ($\Psi_{H_2O}$). As a consequence, water is drawn into the phloem from the xylem, and the turgor pressure near the source increases. The opposite phenomenon happens in the sink organs, where sugars are unloaded from the sieve elements and water potential becomes less negative, which leads water to leave the phloem as well and the pressure to decrease (Figure \ref{fig:munch}). This difference in turgor pressure ($\Delta\Psi_p$) pushes the sap from source to sink \citep{Knoblauch_et_al._2016}. 

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth, angle=0]{images/Munch_schema_tagl.png}
    \caption{Relationship between xylem and phloem. Water enters the phloem at the source and leaves at the sink because of a water potential difference ($\Delta\Psi_w$), while a turgor pressure difference ($\Delta P$) pushes the phloem sap from source to sink. Image taken from \citet{Rascio_2017}.}
    \label{fig:munch}
\end{figure}

Because the phloem sap is rich in nutrients, it is very likely to be attacked by herbivores or parasites. Therefore, the tissue employs some strong defense mechanisms. For instance, plants use callose to occlude wounded sieve tubes and protect them from attacks \citep{Will_et_al._2013}. It can be difficult to do experiments on the phloem, as the sensors that are inserted in the tree to measure phloem transport get sealed off due to the same defense mechanisms. The phloem has been called “the least understood plant tissue” due to such difficulties \citep{Knoblauch_et_al._2016}. Some indirect methods, such as isotope pulse-labelling, are available instead. With this technique, labelled ${}^{13} CO_2$ is taken up by the leaves and can then be traced with the help of an Isotopic Analyzer as it is transported inside the phloem (\citep{Epron_D._et_al._2019}). 
% 1 species Ricinus does not do that. Slightly toxic. For most plants you need indirect methods (labeling or measuring what comes out - proxy). Few methods that are expensive. Also, it is soft, difficult to take samples. 


\subsubsection{Source-sink interrelationship} \label{sec:source}
As stated in the previous section, phloem transport results from a sucrose concentration gradient between source and sink tissues. The source-sink interrelationship plays an important role in regulating both phloem transport and carbon allocation, which determines how the carbon is distributed and used by a plant (accumulation, transport or metabolism). In plants, starch is accumulated as an energy reserve, as opposed to as sucrose, which is soluble and is mostly used for transport \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}. Plants are able to adjust their starch and sucrose production according to different conditions. For example, in \citet{Thorne_and_Koller_1974}, all but one soybean leaves were shaded. After several days, the only source leaf experienced an increase in the rate of net photosynthesis, a decrease in starch concentration and an increase in sucrose concentration.
\smallskip % add soluble sugars list and a bit more about 

Carbon allocation is influenced by the communication between source and sink, for example a decreased sink demand can lead to limitations in the source photosynthetic activity and to a decrease in the speed of phloem transport toward the sinks. This acclimation to changing source-sink relationships ensures a better coordination among source photosynthetic activity, phloem translocation and sink organ demand \citep{Taiz_and_Zeiger_2002}. Communication between source and sink can happen through various means, including through transport sugars like sucrose: low sugar concentrations at the source can cause higher photosynthesis and export towards sink organs, whereas a high sugar concentration can inhibit photosynthesis at the source and encourage growth and storage at the sink, as summarized by Figure \ref{fig:sugar} \citep{Rolland_et_al._2002}. According to the model by \citet{Chiou_and_Bush_1998}, a lower sink demand causes an accumulation of sucrose in the sink, which in turn cause a decrease of the osmotic gradient in the phloem between source and sink. As a consequence, phloem transport slows down, and sugar accumulates in the source (mesophyll cells) as well, which leads to downregulation of photosynthesis. 
%which in turn cause down-regulation of phloem loading at the source. Thus, carbohydrates accumulate in the source (mesophyll cells), which can lead to downregulation of photosynthesis 


\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{images/Source-sink.png}
    \caption{Phloem transport from source (leaves) to sink (young leaves, meristems, flowers, fruit, roots) is affected by sugar concentration. While low sugar concentrations cause a higher photosynthetic activity at the source and a decrease in growth and storage at sink level, the opposite happens when high concentrations of sucrose are available. Image taken from \citet{Rolland_et_al._2002}.}
    \label{fig:sugar}
\end{figure}

Decreased sink demand can happen, for example, if a plant undergoes defruiting, because sink size (the total biomass of sink tissue) gets reduced \citep{Balasubramanian_et_al._2023}. 
% Source-sink relationship can be explored by applying a variety of treatments, such as girdling and defruiting, to plants, and can have applications in agriculture as well, if fruits are the sink organs being studied (probably cut this).
%Several studies have been performed over the years about the relationship between sink demand and photosynthetic activity. 
In \citet{Franck_et_al._2006}, the authors girdled \textit{Coffea arabica} branches at their base. Girdling is a technique where scientists remove a ring of phloem in order to disconnect sources and sinks in the plant. Total soluble sugar concentration ($SSC_m$) and maximal leaf net $CO_2$ assimilation rate ($A_{max}$) were then measured on the mature leaves of the girdled branches (source). The results showed that $A_{max}$ was negatively correlated to $SSC_m$ and that it was higher in branches with higher fruit loads. A conclusion was drawn that there was sink demand feedback on photosynthetic activity \textit{e.g.} low fruit loads demanded less photosynthates, therefore photosynthetic activity decreased. It was concluded that the feedback was mediated by the accumulation of sugars in the leaf phloem. 
\smallskip

Other similar experiments on apple trees \citep{Wünsche_et_al._2005} and peach trees \citep{Duan_et_al._2008} provided similar results, with photosynthetic rate decreasing when the crop load was reduced or removed. \citet{Da_Matta_et_al._2008} proposed a different conclusion regarding their experiment on coffee: the decreased \textit{A} in the leaves of the defruited trees was thought to have been caused not by direct sink feedback, but by the lower stomatal conductance, as (\textit{A}) and (\textit{g}) were correlated. The reason for the lower \textit{g} remained unknown.

\subsubsection{Sink activity and soil cooling} \label{sec:cool}
Sink strength is the ability of a sink organ to import photoassimilates. It is co-regulated by two factors: sink size, which was previously discussed in \ref{sec:source}, and sink activity, \textit{i.e.} the rate of uptake of photoassimilates \citep{Balasubramanian_et_al._2023}. Temperature can have an effect on sink strength by influencing sink activity. For example, roots, which are a major sink organ for trees, can have their sink activity inhibited by soil cooling. If root temperature goes down, the process of respiration - which consumes the sugars produced by photosynthesis and is the main driver for all metabolic activities including root growth - decreases as well. Thus, less carbon is required for growth, and its allocation towards the roots is limited by lower temperatures \citep{Lambers_2008}. 
% growth and respiration are temperature-dependent/ slowed down by T

Soil cooling is not as disruptive as girdling is: since no tissues are damaged, wound responses do not get triggered, and there is a lower risk of changes in secondary metabolism affecting the experiment. Similarly to defruiting, soil cooling has been known to limit photosynthesis, as this thesis will investigate. Previous experiments on the topic were performed on several different species like \textit{Artemisia tridentata} \citep{BassiriRad_et_al._1993}, pine \citep{Day_et_al._1991, Lintunen_et_al._2020}, aspen and spruce \citep{Cai_and_Dang_2002}. The inhibition is thought to be caused by both stomatal and non-stomatal limitation (NSL). The latter includes mesophyll and chloroplast resistance to $CO_2$ diffusion and metabolic restrictions such as RuBisCO inactivation \citep{Signarbieux_et_al._2011, Salmon_et_al._2020}. 
\smallskip

\citet{Day_et_al._1991} observed that stomatal limitation may have had a major role in the decrease of net photosynthetic rate as temperature dropped from 24° C to 7° C. This is suggested by stomatal conductance and intercellular $CO_2$ concentration declining as well. At temperatures below 7°C, intercellular $CO_2$ concentration increased, but the photosynthetic rate kept decreasing, suggesting increasing non-stomatal limitation. This experiment suggests that stomatal and non-stomatal limitation are coordinated with each other during stressful conditions for the plant, with stomata controlling photosynthesis when there is little stress and NSL coming into play with increasing stress. Similar results were obtained with a drought experiment, with NSL increasing during severe drought \citep{Drake_et_al._2017}.
\smallskip

Root cooling for \textit{Artemisia tridentata} also resulted in a limitation of photosynthesis. However, the A (photosynthetic rate) versus $C_i$ (intercellular $CO_2$ concentration) curve did not change with temperature, which suggested stomatal limitation only \citep{BassiriRad_et_al._1993}. 
\smallskip

The processes driving stomatal and non-stomatal limitations are still not fully understood. While they might be a result of sugar accumulation in the sink, they might also be connected to a lower root hydraulic conductivity. When soil temperature goes down, hydraulic conductivity has been shown to also decline. Because the roots take up water less efficiently, the water potential of the entire plant is negatively affected, and stomatal conductance ends up declining as well \citep{Day_et_al._1991, Lintunen_et_al._2020}.

%Cooling a sink tissue inhibits activities that require metabolic energy and results in a decrease in the speed of transport toward the sink: OK
%list of everything that is hypothesized to happen once you cool the roots: hyd cond goes down, less water uptake, phloem transport gets slower, phot slows down due to both sink fb and lower w pot: OK

\subsection{\textit{Betula pendula}}
\textit{Betula pendula}, or European white birch, is a deciduous tree with white bark, drooping outer branches and an average height of 25 m \citep{Vakkari_2009}. Leaves are simple, triangular-shaped, with a dentate margin. It is a Eurosiberian tree distributed in almost all of Europe (but most abundant in Northern Europe) and many parts of Asia and North America \citep{GBIF_Secretariat_2024}. Information on \textit{Betula pendula}'s vascular tissues (Figure \ref{fig:stem}), and on sink limitation is scarce, as studies are usually conducted on model organisms like \textit{Arabidopsis thaliana}.

\begin{figure}[htp]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.2\textwidth]{images/birch_stem.png}
    \caption{Cross section of \textit{Betula pendula}'s stem. Secondary growth with outer phloem tissue (ph), cambial zone (ca) and inner xylem (xy). Image taken from \citet{Hellman_et_al._2018}}
    \label{fig:stem}
\end{figure}

\cleardoublepage

\section{Aim of the thesis} \label{sec:aim}
The present work was conducted in the framework of Xin Zhuang’s Doctorate research. The wider scope of the research is a study on the effects of sink limitation on \textit{Betula pendula} source activity and carbon translocation in the phloem (Zhuang et al., in preparation). Sink activity reduction was achieved by cooling the soil around the roots of 12 saplings down to 4° C, while 8 other trees were left untreated to function as controls.
\smallskip

The experiment consisted of several parts: leaf gas exchange measurements were conducted to gain data on source activity (photosynthesis); sap flow and water potential measurements provided information on xylem transport; isotope labelling was used to study phloem translocation. This thesis will present a part of the results, namely the effects of the sink limitation on canopy photosynthesis, with the hypothesis being that a decreased sink activity will cause a reduction of the leaf photosynthetic activity. For this part of the experiment, gas exchange variables, such as $CO_2$ net assimilation rate and photosynthetic efficiency, were measured with the purpose of understanding how the photosynthetic rate changed with soil temperature. The experiment also aimed at distinguishing the role of stomatal limitation and non-stomatal limitation in reducing photosynthetic activity after the cooling. 
\smallskip

In addition to the gas exchange results, this thesis will also discuss the effect of soil temperature on water potential measurements. Here, the hypothesis is that water potential will decrease as soil temperature decreases. This is because soil cooling is expected to cause a decline in the water uptake capacity of the roots and in water potential values, with stomatal resistance increasing as a result. The lower water uptake is thought to be a contributing factor to the lower photosynthetic rate, in addition to decreased sink activity and sugar accumulation. 

% we limit sink activity + side effect: hydraulic conductivity between root and soil (water has more trouble moving from soil to xylem) - water potential measures that (references): OK


\cleardoublepage

\section{Materials and Methods} \label{sec:materials}
Firstly, section \ref{sec:setup} discusses how the experiment was set up and the conditions under which it was performed. 

Then, section \ref{sec:measure} (Measurements) talks about the variables that were measured and the instruments that were used in order to study the effects of soil cooling on photosynthetic rate and hydraulic status of the saplings.

Section \ref{sec:stat} is a description of the statistical analysis that was conducted to achieve the results.

\subsection{Experiment setup} \label{sec:setup}
I witnessed and worked on the experiment during my time as a trainee at the University of Helsinki, under the mentorship of Xin Zhuang and the supervision of Dr. Yann Salmon. The experiment took place at the Viikki Campus (Department of Forest Sciences, Faculty of Agriculture and Forestry), at the University of Helsinki, in a greenhouse environment, starting from June 20th 2023 and ending on August 21st of the same year. The environmental conditions in the greenhouse were 21° C and 60\% relative humidity on average. The setup involved 20 birch saplings (\textit{Betula pendula}), of approximately 3-5 years of age and 2-2.5 m tall. The trees were replanted in 20-liter pots with a mixture of forest peat and original nursery field soil, and placed in the greenhouse a week before the start of the measurements. 
\smallskip

The LAUDA thermostat (Figure \ref{fig:lauda}) was used to bring temperature down to 4 °C. The thermostat consists of a refrigeration unit and a tubing system, which was filled with anti-freeze \citep{Lauda_1989}. The silicone tubes were buried in the pots so that they were closer to the roots, cooling them more efficiently. Further insulation was achieved by putting the pots into coolbags and wrapping foam around the tubes (Figure \ref{fig:treated}). 


\begin{figure}
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth, angle=270]{lauda.jpg}
    \caption{Cooling system connected to Lauda's external circulation. Silicone tubes are buried in the pots, which are insulated thanks to coolbags.}
    \label{fig:lauda}
\end{figure}
\smallskip


\subsection{Measurements} \label{sec:measure}
Measurements were taken on five trees at a time. Every batch, numbered from 1 to 4, consisted of two untreated trees (controls) and three trees that had been cooled down (treated trees). The first group was measured from June 30th to July 13th; the second batch was measured from July 13th to August 1st; the third group was measured from August 1st to August 7th; the fourth batch was measured from August 7th to August 10th. 
\smallskip

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth, angle=270]{treated_trees_2.jpg}
    \caption{Treated trees in the greenhouse.}
    \label{fig:treated}
\end{figure}

The instruments used during the experiment were K-type thermocouples for measuring soil temperature, the LI-6800 (LI-COR’s fourth generation portable photosynthesis system) for measuring gas exchange, and a pressure chamber for water potential. 
\smallskip

\subsubsection{Soil temperature measurements}
K-type thermocouples are sensors containing Chromel and Alumel conductors. The difference in voltage produced by the thermocouple can be used to measure a difference in temperature \citep{Hunt_1964}. The thermocouples employed in this experiment were had a 2 mm diameter and could sense a maximum temperature of +250° C.

\subsubsection{Gas exchange}
The difference in canopy source activity between control and treated saplings was estimated thanks to four leaf gas exchange variables: $CO_2$ net assimilation rate (\textit{A}), photosynthetic efficiency (\textit{$A/C_i$}), $H_2O$ evapotranspiration rate (\textit{E}) and stomatal conductance to water vapor (\textit{gsw}). $CO_2$ net assimilation is defined as a measure of the difference between photosynthesis and respiration, while evapotranspiration measures the rate of water vapor loss. Both variables are connected to stomatal conductance, as $CO_2$ and $H_2O$ diffuse mostly through the stomata \citep{LI-COR_Inc._2020}. Photosynthetic efficiency, which is a normalization of \textit{A} by $C_i$ (intercellular $CO_2$), was calculated and then used as a variable, in order to have some data about non-stomatal limitation as well. The ratio remains constant if both \textit{A} and \textit{$C_i$} are decreasing, which indicates stomatal control, whereas decreasing values indicate NSL, as \textit{A} is still decreasing despite constant or increasing \textit{$C_i$} \citep{Drake_et_al._2017}. % is this right?
The four variables provide different information about photosynthetic activity, with \textit{A} and \textit{$A/C_i$} measuring the rate of photosynthesis directly, and \textit{E} and \textit{gsw} offering information about the degree of opening of the stomata. A decline in the gas exchange variables indicates decreased photosynthetic activity. 
\smallskip

\textit{A}, \textit{E}, \textit{gsw} and \textit{$C_i$} were all measured with the LI-6800, after burying the tubes in the pots, turning the cooling system on, and waiting for the soil to cool down for several hours and then at least 3 days for plants to reach a steady state. 
\smallskip

The LI-6800 (Figure \ref{fig:licor}) can non-destructively measure photosynthetic processes happening at leaf-level. Several leaf chambers of different dimensions are available; for this experiment, a $6-cm^2-$area chamber was used \citep{LI-COR_Inc._2020}.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.4\textwidth, angle=270]{images/licor_1.jpg}
    \caption{Portable Photosynthesis System closed onto birch leaf.}
    \label{fig:licor}
\end{figure}

Before measuring, a reference needs to be set for $CO_2$  concentration, humidity, temperature and light going into the chamber: for our experiment, a $CO_2$  concentration of 400 $\mu$mol $mol^{-1}$  and 60\% relative humidity were chosen. The temperature was set at 26° C and the light was set at 500 $\mu$mol $m^{-1}s^{-1}$. 
\smallskip

After the chamber is closed onto a leaf, two variables, $CO_2$  net assimilation rate (\textit{A}) and $H_2O$ evapo-transpiration rate (\textit{E}), can be obtained by using the infrared gas analysers (IRGA) next to the leaf chamber (Figure \ref{fig:chamber}).
Firstly, the gas analysers measure the flow rate ($\mu$mol air $s^{-1}$) and the $CO_2$ and $H_2O$  concentrations (\textit{$\mu_0$}, \textit{$c_0$}, \textit{$w_0$} respectively) before entering the leaf chamber (reference). $CO_2$ and water vapor concentrations (\textit{$c_a$} and \textit{$w_a$} respectively) are then measured again after coming out of the chamber (sample) \citep{LI-COR_Inc._2020}.  
\smallskip

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{images/licor_chamber.png}
    \caption{Schematic of LI-6800 gas exchange system. The gas analysers measured flow rate, $CO_2$, $H_2O$ as they enter and then as they exit the leaf chamber. Image from \citet{LI-COR_Inc._2020}.}
    \label{fig:chamber}
\end{figure}

\noindent It is not necessary to directly measure the flow rate exiting the chamber ($\mu_a$). The water vapor released by the leaf can be added to the $\mu_0$ to obtain this value.

\begin{equation}
    \mu_a = \mu_0 + sE
    \label{eq:flow}
\end{equation}
where \textit{s} represents leaf area.
\smallskip

After these measurements, the variables \textit{A} and \textit{E} can be computed from the difference in concentration between reference and sample.

\noindent Transpiration, on a leaf area (\textit{s}) basis, is calculated as: 
\begin{equation}
    sE = \mu_a w_a - \mu_0 w_0
    \label{eq:transpiration}
\end{equation}

\noindent Equation \ref{eq:flow} and \ref{eq:transpiration} can be rearranged to calculate $H_2O$ evapo-transpiration rate (\textit{E}):

\begin{equation}
    E = \frac{\mu_0(w_a - w_0)}{s(1 - w_a)}
\end{equation}

\noindent The equation to calculate the $CO_2$ net assimilation rate is similar to equation \ref{eq:transpiration}, but in this case the gas is being taken up by the leaf and fixed during the Calvin cycle, so $c_a$ is lower than $c_0$:

\begin{equation}
    sA = \mu_0 c_0 - \mu_a c_a
    \label{eq:assimilation}
\end{equation}

\noindent By rearranging equations \ref{eq:flow} and \ref{eq:assimilation}, we get:

\begin{equation}
    A = \frac{\mu_0 [c_0 - c_a (\frac{1 - w_0}{1 - w_a})]}{s}
\end{equation}

Stomatal conductance to water vapor (\textit{gsw}) and intercellular $CO_2$  concentration are calculated thanks to other measurements taken by LI-6800, including leaf temperature \citep{LI-COR_Inc._2020}.
\smallskip

We measured \textit{A}, \textit{E}, \textit{gsw} and \textit{$C_i$} on multiple days for each batch. For example, the saplings from batch 1 (treated trees BQ1, BQ2, BQ3 and controls BC1 and BC2) were measured on June 30th and on July 4th, 10th and 13th. For each tree, three leaves (replicates) were selected to be measured. Each leaf was measured three times, leaving about ten seconds between each measurement, and the three values were then averaged to obtain the individual leaf value. This was done in order to limit the impact of small fluctuations in the measured signal. As an example, Table \ref{table:controls} shows the measurements that were taken on July 4th for the control trees. For each tree, measurements from the three leaves were then averaged to get the final value to use for our analysis. 


\begin{table}[H]
\centering
\caption{Measurements taken on July 4th for the control trees from batch 1 (BC1 and BC2). The variables are evapotranspiration rate (\textit{E}), $CO_2$ assimilation rate (\textit{A}), intercellular $CO_2$ concentration (\textit{$C_i$}) and stomatal conductance (\textit{gsw}).}

\begin{tabular}{| l | l | l | l | l | l | l |}
\hline
\small{TIME} & \small{TREE ID} & \small{REPL} & \small{E (mol $m^{-2} s^{-1}$)} & \small{A ($\mu mol$ $m^{-2} s^{-1}$)} & \small{$C_i$ ($\mu mol$ $mol^{-1}$)} & \small{gsw (mol $m^{-2} s^{-1}$)} \\
\hline
10:41:36 & BC1 & 1 & $1,77x10^{-3}$  & 11,23 & 244,93 & 0,14 \\
