\subsubsection{Water potential} 
The pressure chamber (Figure \ref{fig:pressure}), also known as Scholander chamber, is a device for measuring water potential by applying pressure to a leaf thanks to the nitrogen tank connected to the chamber. For our experiment, two leaves were taken from each tree and inserted in the chamber one at a time, with the cut end of the stem exposed outside of it. Pressure was then applied until water came out at the surface. This is the amount of pressure that is equal and opposite to the leaf water potential. Therefore, a high value of pressure indicates a low water potential, which signals a stronger pulling force at the tree canopy. This means that the tree is experiencing water stress. Maximum instrument operating pressure was 100 Bar \citep{PMS_Instrument_Company_2009}.
\smallskip

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth]{images/pressure_chamber.jpg}
    \caption{Pressure chamber in the greenhouse. The leaf is inserted in the chamber and the petiole can be observed through a lens, as pressure grows, until water comes out of it.}
    \label{fig:pressure}
\end{figure}

%second image?
Measurements were taken in the early afternoon to make sure they were comparable, as water potential changes during the day, usually having the most negative values at midday \citep{Morandi_et_al._2010}. For each tree, two leaves were measured and then an average was calculated and used for the data analysis.

%$ \prescript{13}{}{\(CO_2\)} $

\subsection{Statistical analysis} \label{sec:stat}
For the statistical analysis, I used the programming language R \citep{R_Core_Team_2023}.
\smallskip

The first part of the analysis (section \ref{sec:first} in the Results) tested whether there was a significant difference between the leaf gas exchange values of cooled trees and control trees by analysing four variables: \textit{A}, \textit{$A/C_i$}, \textit{E} and \textit{gsw}. The possibility of a significant difference among the four batches had to be taken into consideration as well, as they were measured during different parts of the growing season, starting from early July and ending in mid August.
\smallskip

Employing a parametric ANOVA was not possible, as the distribution of the data was not normal nor were the residuals of the ANOVA analysis. Data transformation did not solve the issue. Therefore, these data were tested for difference using the Scheirer–Ray–Hare test with a significance level of $0.05$. The Scheirer–Ray–Hare test is a non-parametric test used for a two-way factorial design \citep{Mangiafico_2016}.    
\smallskip

I used the package \texttt{rcompanion} \citep{Mangiafico_2024}. An example of the code used for the this part, for the variable \textit{A}, is given below:

\begin{verbatim}
    SRH_A <- scheirerRayHare(avg.A ~ batch + treatment, data=licor_avg)
\end{verbatim}

The second part of the analysis (section \ref{sec:second} in the Results) aimed at studying whether there was a significant effect of soil cooling (and soil temperature in general) on the same four gas exchange variables. $P<0.05$ was considered to be statistically significant here as well.
Firstly, I used a classical linear regression. The code below is an example for the \textit{A} variable: 

\begin{verbatim}
    fitA <- lm(licor_avg$avg.A ~ licor_avg$batch + licor_avg$soil_temperature)
\end{verbatim}

The model was validated with the help of diagnostic plots \citep{Zuur_2009} that represented the residuals, \textit{i.e.} the difference between the fitted values and the observed values. The QQ-plot of the residuals for the linear regression shows that the points are not in a line, so the distribution of the residuals of the linear regression was not normal (Figure \ref{fig:residuals}). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/qq_residuals_3.png}
    \caption{QQ-plot of the residuals for normality for the relationship between $CO_2$ net assimilation rate and soil temperature.}
    \label{fig:residuals}
\end{figure}

After establishing that classical linear regression was not suitable, I tried a generalized linear model with a gamma distribution. This distribution looks like a Gaussian distribution skewed to the left \citep{Zuur_2009}, which is similar to how the distribution for \textit{A} values appears (Figure \ref{fig:distrib}). This model was used for \textit{A} and \textit{$A/C_i$}.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A_distrib.png}
    \caption{Histogram showing the distribution of $CO_2$ net assimilation (A) in cooled and control trees. The distribution is slightly skewed to the left.}
    \label{fig:distrib}
\end{figure}

An example of the code is given below for \textit{A}:

\begin{verbatim}
    gammaA <- glm(formula = licor_avg$avg.A ~ 
              licor_avg$batch + licor_avg$soil_temperature,
              family = Gamma(), data = licor_avg)
\end{verbatim}

This model was also validated with the help of diagnostic plots. Figure \ref{fig:diagnostics} shows the plot of response residuals (observed minus fitted values) for \textit{A}. There is a lack of pattern, which is to be expected when the data are not normally distributed. This confirms that the model is a good fit for the data \citep{Zuur_2009}. %If there was a variable that was important and we had not considered, then a pattern would appear

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.6\textwidth]{images/residuals_gamma.png}
    \caption{Diagnostic plot for the gamma distribution model for the relationship between $CO_2$ net assimilation rate and soil temperature on. The plot shows response residuals (observed minus fitted values).}
    \label{fig:diagnostics}
\end{figure}

The response of the other two variables (\textit{E} and \textit{gsw}) to the soil temperature was also non-linear, even after data transformation was attempted. Therefore, the Generalized Additive Model (GAM) was employed instead of the Generalized Linear Model. The Generalized Additive Model is suitable to study non-linear relationships and fit the data better than the gamma distribution.
\smallskip

Here is an example for \textit{E}. I used the package \texttt{mgcv} \citep{Wood_2017}:

\begin{verbatim}
   gamE_ <- gam(licor_avg_2$avg.E ~ 
   licor_avg_2$batch + s(licor_avg_2$soil_temperature, by=licor_avg_2$batch))
\end{verbatim}
    
The same models and the same validation process were chosen for the third part of the analysis (section \ref{sec:third} in the Results), where the effect of water potential on the four gas exchange variables was examined, with the following code (for \textit{A}):

\begin{verbatim}
    gammaA2 <- glm(licor_avg$avg.A ~ 
               licor_avg_3$batch + licor_avg_3$water_potential,
               data=licor_avg_3, family=Gamma())
\end{verbatim}


\cleardoublepage

\section{Results} \label{sec:res}
This section will discuss results pertaining to batch 1, 2 and 4. Batch 3 will not be included due to anomalies found throughout the data analysis. 
\smallskip

\subsection{Comparison between gas exchange values in control trees and cooled trees} \label{sec:first}
The first part of the analysis aimed at comparing the photosynthetic activity in control trees and treated trees.  
\textit{A}, \textit{E} and \textit{gsw} values were significantly different between the two groups, with the control trees having significantly higher values than the treated trees (p-value$<10^{-5}$). A boxplot, generated using the package \texttt{ggplot2} \citep{Wickham_2016}, was chosen to represent the distribution of data per treatment. The box includes the values between the first and the third quartile and is divided by a line, the median. The "whiskers" show the values outside of the central 50\%. The boxplots (Figure \ref{fig:A_con_sign}, Figure \ref{fig:E_with_sign} and Figure \ref{fig:gsw_with_sign}) also highlight this difference between the two treatments: the two distributions show very little overlapping. 

The median of \textit{A} values for the controls was about 9 $\mu mol m^{-2} s^{-1}$, whereas the median for the cooled trees was less than 5 $\mu mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$ (Figure \ref{fig:A_con_sign}). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/A_con_sign.png}
    \caption{$CO_2$ net assimilation in control and cooled trees. The boxplot on the left (control trees) shows significantly higher values and a higher median that the boxplot on the right (treated trees).}
    \label{fig:A_con_sign}
\end{figure}

The median of \textit{E} values for the controls is about $2x10^{-3}$ $mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$, while the median for the treated trees is about $5x10^{-4}$ $molm^{-2}s^{-1}$ (Figure \ref{fig:E_with_sign}). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/E_with_sign.png}
    \caption{Evapotranspiration rate in control and cooled trees.}
    \label{fig:E_with_sign}
\end{figure}

The median of \textit{gsw} values for the controls was about 0.14 $mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$, whereas the median for the cooled trees was less than 0.05 $mol m^{-2}s^{-1}$ (Figure \ref{fig:gsw_with_sign}). 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/gsw_with_sign.png}
    \caption{Stomatal conductance to water vapor in control and cooled trees.}
    \label{fig:gsw_with_sign}
\end{figure}

Photosynthetic efficiency was also significantly different between control trees and treated trees, however the p-value was higher (0.007). There was a significant difference among the batches as well (p-value=0.04): only batch 4 had significantly different values between the two groups (0.01), whereas for the other two batches, the p-values were higher than 0.05. Boxplot \ref{fig:A_Ci_with_sign} shows that control trees have higher values than treated trees, but the medians of the two groups are closer to one another (0.03 $mol m^{-2} s{-1}$ for the controls and about 0.02 $mol m^{-2} s{-1}$ for the treated trees). There is a lot of overlapping between the two distributions.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A_Ci_with_sign.png}
    \caption{Photosynthetic efficiency in control and cooled trees.}
    \label{fig:A_Ci_with_sign}
\end{figure}


\subsection{Effect of soil temperature on leaf gas exchange} \label{sec:second}
Having established that the cooled trees have significantly lower values for the gas exchange variables, the second part of the analysis adds to the first part by quantifying the effect of low soil temperatures (explanatory variable) on the leaf gas exchange variables (response variables). The impact of soil temperature on three gas exchange variables, \textit{A}, \textit{E} and \textit{gsw}, proved to be significant. 
\smallskip

The relationship between \textit{A} and soil temperature had a p-value=$2.8x10^{-5}$ for the slope of the model. All batches show a decrease in $CO_2$ assimilation as temperature decreases (Figure \ref{fig:A2}). However, there is a significant difference among the batches as well (0.03): they are all significant individually, but batch 4 has the lowest p-value (0.009), with the cooled trees values being closer to one another and less scattered. Another noticeable characteristic of the plot is that \textit{A} values for control trees get progressively lower as time passes and as the growing season progress, with batch 1 - which was measured earlier in the season - having the highest values, and batch 4 having the lowest values. 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A_def.png}
    \caption{The scatter plot shows the effect of soil temperature on $CO_2$ assimilation. Batches 1, 2 and 4 are represented by different colors, whereas two different shapes are used for control (circle) and treated (triangle) trees. All batches show an increase as temperature increases.}
    \label{fig:A2}
\end{figure}

Soil temperature had a highly significant effect on \textit{E}, with batch 1 having the most significant p-value ($7.7x10^{-6}$) and batch 2 and 4 having p-values of $3.5x10^{-5}$ and $3x10^{-3}$. Batch 1 has the highest control values here as well.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/E_def.png}
    \caption{The scatter plot shows the effect of soil temperature on the $H_2O$ evapotraspiration rate. All batches show an increase as temperature increases.}
    \label{fig:E2}
\end{figure}

The scatter plot representing the effect of soil temperature on \textit{gsw} shows a similar trend to the previous plot, with p-values of $3.5x10^{-7}$ for batch 1, $3.8xx10^{-6}$ for batch 2 and $8xx10^{-4}$. 

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/Rgsw_def.png}
    \caption{The scatter plot shows the effect of soil temperature on the stomatal conductance. All batches show an increase as temperature increases.}
    \label{fig:gsw2}
\end{figure}

These last two plots show the clearest relationship between response variable and explanatory variable. The cooled trees values for \textit{E} and \textit{gsw} have lower, less scattered values than the ones for \textit{A}, creating steeper slopes. % quantify that with percentages?
\smallskip

The relationship between \textit{$A/C_i$} and soil temperature is significant when considering all three batches (p=0.04), but the the relationship with each individual batch is not significant (the p-values are 0.19, 0.42 and 0.06 for batch 1, 2 and 4, respectively), as a lot of the cooled trees have high photosynthetic efficiency values (Figure \ref{fig:A_over_Ci2}).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A_Ci_def.png}
    \caption{The scatter plot shows the effect of soil temperature on photosynthetic efficiency. The individual batches do not show a significant increase as temperature increases.}
    \label{fig:A_over_Ci2}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Effect of water potential on leaf gas exchange} \label{sec:third}
The third part of the analysis looked at the water potential data. Firstly, the effect of soil temperature on water potential was examined using a gamma distribution model. With a p-value=0.446, there was no significant relationship between the explanatory variable and the response variable. The plot (Figure \ref{fig:soil_t_wat}) shows very scattered data. While the control trees have higher soil temperature than the cooled trees, the distribution of water potential values is not as clear, with control and cooled trees from the same batch often having similar values \textit{e.g.} most water potential values from batch 2 range from about -7 bars to about -9 bars. % unclear? vague?

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/soil_t_vs_wat.png}
    \caption{There is no significant effect of soil temperature on water potential values. The scattered values are an indication of the lack of a significant relationship between the two variables.}
    \label{fig:soil_t_wat}
\end{figure}

A further analysis was made to establish whether water potential had affected the four gas exchange variables. Here, the effect was not significant for any of the response variables. P-values for the relationship between \textit{A} values and water potential were 0.0727 for batch 1, 0.22 for batch 2 and 0.17 for batch 4. Figure \ref{fig:A3_def} shows that, similarly to the previous plot (Figure \ref{fig:soil_t_wat}), control and cooled trees from batch 2 have a similar distribution, confirming that $CO_2$ assimilation is not significantly affected by water potential for this batch. Batch 1 and 4 do show a decrease in $CO_2$ assimilation as water potential increases, with control trees having lower water potential values than cooled trees. However, this effect is small, as confirmed by the p-values. % regression driven by controls having lower values for water potential and higher values for evapotranspiration/ other gas exch values - range of wp is too small

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth]{images/A3_def.png}
    \caption{There is no significant effect of water potential on net $CO_2$ assimilation. The values for the three batches are scattered and confirm the lack of relationship between the two variables.}
    \label{fig:A3_def}
\end{figure}

The relationship between $H_2O$ evapotranspiration and water potential is only significant for batch 1 (p-value=0.01), which shows lower water potential values for control trees and higher values for cooled trees. Thus, there is a decrease in evapotranspiration values as water potential increases. The other two batches do not have significant p-values (0.06 for batch 2 and 0.21 for batch 4). The relationship between stomatal conductance and water potential is similar to the previous one between evapotranspiration and water potential, with the first batch being significant (p-value=0.006) and the other two not being significant (0.1 and 0.26).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/E3_def.png}
    \caption{Batch 1 shows a significant decrease in $H_2O$ evapotranspiration as water potential grows. The relationship between explanatory variable and response variable is not significant for the other two batches.}
    \label{fig:E3_def}
\end{figure}

Finally, $A/Ci$ (photosynthetic efficiency) is not significantly affected by water potential, with p-values of 0.46, 0.82 and 0.31 for the three batches (Figure \ref{fig:A.Ci3_def}).

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A.Ci3_def.png}
    \caption{The relationship between water potential and photosynthetic efficiency is not significant for any of the three batches.}
    \label{fig:A.Ci3_def}
\end{figure}

\cleardoublepage

\section{Discussion and future perspectives} 

In section Aim of the thesis (section \ref{sec:aim}), two hypothesis had been put forward. The first one proposed that the soil cooling would cause a reduced sink activity, which would result in a decreased rate of photosynthesis. This hypothesis was investigated by comparing the leaf gas exchange values of cooled trees and control trees (section \ref{sec:first}) and by studying the effect of soil temperature (explanatory variable) on the leaf gas exchange variables (response variables) (section \ref{sec:second}).
\smallskip

The second hypothesis suggested that low soil temperature would have an effect on water potential, which in turn would affect the stomatal conductance and the photosynthetic rate, contributing to their decline. The impact of soil temperature on water potential and the subsequent effect of water potential on leaf gas exchange were discussed in section \ref{sec:third}.
\smallskip

When it comes to the first hypothesis, cooled trees had significantly lower values than control trees for three of the gas exchange variables: $CO_2$ net assimilation rate, $H_2O$ evapotranspiration rate and stomatal conductance to water vapor (section \ref{sec:first}). Control trees' values were highest for batch 1 and lowest for batch 4, probably due to the first batch having been measured earlier in the growing season, in the first half of July, when photosynthetic activity is at its peak \citep{Oksanen_2003}. 
\smallskip  

Unlike the other three gas exchange variables, photosynthetic efficiency values ($A/C_i$) were not significantly different for each individual batch. As $A/C_i$ had been chosen as a variable to get data on non-stomatal limitation, these results suggest that the decrease in photosynthetic rate might be due to stomatal limitation, while non-stomatal limitation seems to have a minor role.
\smallskip 

The analysis in section \ref{sec:second} had similar results, with soil temperature having a significant impact on the same three variables, but not on the photosynthetic efficiency. 
\smallskip
% We can conclude that they are all negatively affected by low soil temperature. Photosynthetic efficiency appears to not be significantly affected. Therefore, the role of non-stomatal limitation seems to have been marginal in affecting the rate of photosynthesis (cut)
\smallskip 

As previously discussed in section \ref{sec:cool}, similar experiments on other trees species had reached several different conclusions, with \citet{BassiriRad_et_al._1993} also reporting a major role of stomatal limitation of photosynthesis, whereas \citet{Day_et_al._1991} reported both stomatal and non-stomatal limitation, and \citet{Cai_and_Dang_2002} found no significant impact of soil temperature on stomatal conductance. % what conclusion could potentially be drawn from this?
\smallskip

The second hypothesis was not supported by the results for the third part of the analysis. Leaf water potential, which was expected to decrease with the decrease of soil temperature, was not significantly impacted by the cooling. Furthermore, water potential had no significant effect on the four gas exchange variables, with one exception: in batch 1, \textit{E} and \textit{gsw} values significantly increased as water potential declined. These results differ from previous experiment on the same topic, such as the experiment by \citet{Lintunen_et_al._2020}, where a decline in soil-to-leaf hydraulic conductivity followed a cooling treatment and coincided with a decline in stomatal conductance. 

It is not surprising that this soil cooling experiment had different results than \citet{Lintunen_et_al._2020}, as the water potential values that were measured during our experiment only range from about -6.6 bar to -13.6 bar. If compared with other experiments where trees underwent water stress, \textit{e.g.} \citet{Salmon_et_al._2020}, which investigated the effects of drought on stomatal conductance, we can see that water potential for \textit{Betula pendula} can reach values as low as -25 bars for water-stressed trees. Another experiment \citep{Hölttä_et_al._2017}, during which trees were given a notching treatment (incision in the xylem), also showed a much larger range of water potential values, almost reaching -2.0 MPa (-20 bars), with $A/C_i$ significantly decreasing as water potential decreased (Figure \ref{fig:holltta}. On the contrary, the soil cooling treatment we performed did not have a strong impact on water potential, which in turn had a small or non-existent effect on the four gas exchange variables. 
\smallskip

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering 
\graphicspath{ {./images/} }
    \includegraphics[width=0.7\textwidth]{images/A_Ci_vs_war_pot_modificato.png}
    \caption{Experiment by \citet{Hölttä_et_al._2017}. After a notching treatment, aimed at lowering hydraulic conductance and water potential, photosynthetic efficiency ($A/C_i$) decreased significantly with decreasing water potential values. The red line shows the much smaller range of values that we had after the soil cooling treatment.}
    \label{fig:holltta}
\end{figure}

As previously stated, the results examined in this thesis are a part of Xin Zhuang's PhD on carbon translocation in \textit{Betula pendula}. Therefore, further analysis will be conducted to put the results of the present work into context. In particular, leaf and bark sugar samples were also taken from each batch once during the gas exchange measurements and then a second time after finishing all measurements. These samples will be analyzed to get information about the feedback mechanism that is believed to cause the decline in photosynthetic rate that follows the soil cooling (section \ref{sec:source}).  
\smallskip

Further analysis will also be needed to better understand the last part of the Results (section \ref{sec:third}). Hydraulic conductivity will be calculated from the xylem sap flow rate and the soil to leaf water potential difference (Equation \ref{eq:conductivity}) so that its relationship to soil temperature and its impact on gas exchange values can be seen directly.  
\smallskip

In addition to studying the sink-source relationship, the experiment also included the isotope pulse-labelling of the trees with $ \prescript{13}{}{CO_2} $ in order to track carbon transport in the phloem and investigate a possible limitation in translocation due to the soil cooling. 
\smallskip

In conclusion, while the presence of a decline in the photosynthetic rate as a result of direct sink feedback was supported by the data, water potential seemed unaffected by soil temperature and did not have a key role in driving the photosynthetic rate. The lack of recent experiments that utilize soil cooling as a technique to study sink limitation highlight the importance of conducting research on this particular branch of tree physiology. 

\cleardoublepage

\section{Appendix 1}

This is the code used for the data analysis. 

\begin{verbatim}
# importing gas exchange data
licor_1 <- read.csv("data/final_version_with_comment_1a - Copia.csv", sep = ";",
header = TRUE, dec =",")

licor_1$treatment <- factor(licor_1$treatment) 

# creating A/Ci column 
licor_1$A.Ci <- licor_1$A/licor_1$Ci

# removing outliers
licor_2 <- subset(licor_1, licor_1$comment != "outlier")

#calculating the average of the three values per leaf
library(dplyr)

licor_avg_1 <- licor_2%>%
  group_by(X, date, tree.id, batch, treatment, replicate, Y)%>%
  dplyr::summarise(avg.E_1=mean(E), avg.A_1=mean(A), avg.Ca_1=mean(Ca),
  avg.Ci_1=mean(Ci), avg.gsw_1=mean(gsw), avg.A.Ci_1=mean(A.Ci),
  avg.VPcham_1=mean(VPcham), avg.VPDleaf_1=mean(VPDleaf),
  avg.Q_1=mean(Q_out))%>%
  as.data.frame()

# calculating the average of measurements
  for each tree on each day
licor_avg_2 <- licor_avg_1%>%
  group_by(Y, date, tree.id, batch, treatment)%>%
  dplyr::summarise(avg.E_2=mean(avg.E_1), avg.A_2=mean(avg.A_1),
  avg.Ca_2=mean(avg.Ca_1), avg.Ci_2=mean(avg.Ci_1), avg.gsw_2=mean(avg.gsw_1),
  avg.A.Ci_2=mean(avg.A.Ci_1), avg.VPcham_2=mean(avg.VPcham_1),
  avg.VPDleaf_2=mean(avg.VPDleaf_1), avg.Q_2=mean(avg.Q_1))%>%
  as.data.frame()

# removing batch 3
licor_avg_2 <- subset(licor_avg_2, licor_avg_2$batch != "3")

# converting batch from numeric to factor
licor_avg_2$batch <- factor(licor_avg_2$batch)

# GAS EXCHANGE VARIABLES ~ BATCH + TREATMENT
library(rcompanion)

# Scheirer–Ray–Hare test (nonparametric test used for two-way
factorial design) - all significant

SRH_A <- scheirerRayHare(avg.A_2 ~ batch + treatment, data=licor_avg_2)

SHR_E <- scheirerRayHare(avg.E_2 ~ batch + treatment, data=licor_avg_2)

SHR_gsw <- scheirerRayHare(avg.gsw_2 ~ batch + treatment, data=licor_avg_2)

SHR_A.Ci <- scheirerRayHare(avg.A.Ci_2 ~ batch + treatment, data=licor_avg_2)

# checking whether individual batches are significant
# by creating subsets for each batch
licor_avg_b1 <- subset(licor_avg_2, licor_avg_2$batch == "1")
licor_avg_b2 <- subset(licor_avg_2, licor_avg_2$batch == "2")
licor_avg_b4 <- subset(licor_avg_2, licor_avg_2$batch == "4")

# Kruskal-Wallis test:
# batches are not individually significant for A/Ci
kr_1 <- kruskal.test(licor_avg_b1$avg.A.Ci_2 ~ licor_avg_b1$treatment) 
# p-value=0.1 

kr_2 <- kruskal.test(licor_avg_b2$avg.A.Ci_2 ~ licor_avg_b2$treatment) 
# p-value=0.37

kr_4 <- kruskal.test(licor_avg_b4$avg.A.Ci_2 ~ licor_avg_b4$treatment) 
# p-value=0.01

# SOIL TEMPERATURE
# importing soil temperature data
temp <- read.table("data/CR1000X_Yann_XinCooling.dat", header=TRUE, sep=",", 
skip=3, na.strings = "NAN")

# removing the days before and after gas exchange measurements
temp_2 <- temp[-c(1:40418, 273468:306236), ]

# changing column names and date format
colnames(temp_2) <- c('Date', 'N', 'Min', 'Smp', 'cool1', 'cool2', 'cool3', 
'contr1', 'contr2')
library(stringr)
temp_2[c('date', 'time')] <- str_split_fixed(temp_2$Date, ' ', 2)
temp_2$date <- as.Date(temp_2$date, format = "%Y-%m-%d")
temp_2$date <- format(temp_2$date, "%d/%m/%Y")

# calculating the average for temperature values (each day)
temp_3 <- temp_2%>%
  group_by(date)%>%
  dplyr::summarise(Smp=mean(Smp), cool1=mean(cool1), cool2=mean(cool2),
  cool3=mean(cool3), contr1=mean(contr1),  contr2=mean(contr2))%>%
  as.data.frame()

# ordering by date
temp_3 <- temp_3[order(as.Date(temp_3$date, format="%d/%m/%Y")), ]

# on 13/7 we measured 2 batches (batch 1 in the morning and 2 in the afternoon): 
# we need 2 values of mean 
mean(temp[115163:118066,5])
mean(temp[115163:118066,6])
mean(temp[115163:118066,7])
mean(temp[115163:118066,8])
mean(temp[115163:118066,9])

mean(temp[118067:120922,5])
mean(temp[118067:120922,6])
mean(temp[118067:120922,7])
mean(temp[118067:120922,8])
mean(temp[118067:120922,9])

# keeping only the days during which we measured gas exchange
temp_4 <- temp_3[temp_3$date %in% c('30/06/2023', '03/07/2023', '04/07/2023', 
'10/07/2023', '13/07/2023', '19/07/2023',  '21/07/2023', '25/07/2023',
'28/07/2023', '01/08/2023',  '04/08/2023', '07/08/2023', '09/08/2023', 
'10/08/2023'), ]

# creating a new column for soil temperature, 
# with mean values for each day and each tree
licor_avg_2$soil_temperature <- c(5.165599, 5.244229, 6.994229, 2.634512, 
3.064366, 17.08293, 16.39777, 3.684478, 2.368306, 3.565989, 3.070011, 1.980472, 
3.364987, 16.68514, 15.79022, 5.792202, 21.93107, 4.238358, 23.07499, 3.383498,
3.13424, 4.337276, 5.644117, 5.697607, 3.102319, 6.945484, 24.66709, 25.19100,
24.82654, 24.27996, 3.331607, 2.011076, 3.165969, 25.47543, 26.42160, 4.064173, 
2.589215, 4.854806, 8.183644, 5.437522, 33.75890, 33.67237, 7.398282, 8.350280, 
5.978569, 7.078955, 5.985372, 6.020313, 24.60876, 24.56076)

# GAS EXCHANGE VS SOIL TEMPERATURE

# gamma distribution for A
gammaA <- glm(formula = licor_avg_2$avg.A_2 ~licor_avg_2$batch +
licor_avg_2$soil_temperature, family = Gamma(), data = licor_avg_2) # 2.81e-05 ***

# model validation for gamma distribution
EP <- resid(gammaA, type = "pearson")
ED <- resid(gammaA, type = "deviance")
mu <- predict(gammaA, type = "response")
E <- licor_avg_2$avg.A_2 - mu
EP2 <- E / sqrt(0.2150349 * mu)
op <- par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(x = mu, y = E, main = "Response residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP, main = "Pearson residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP2, main = "Pearson residuals scaled")
plot(x = mu, y = ED, main = "Deviance residuals")
par(op) # no pattern
dev.off()

# individual batches
gammaA_b1 <- glm(avg.A_2[licor_avg_2$batch == "1"] ~ 
licor_avg_2$soil_temperature[licor_avg_2$batch == "1"], 
data=licor_avg_2, family=Gamma()) # 0.01

gammaA_b2 <- glm(avg.A_2[licor_avg_2$batch == "2"] ~ 
licor_avg_2$soil_temperature[licor_avg_2$batch == "2"],
data=licor_avg_2, family=Gamma()) # 0.01

gammaA_b4 <- glm(avg.A_2[licor_avg_2$batch == "4"] ~ 
licor_avg_2$soil_temperature[licor_avg_2$batch == "4"],
data=licor_avg_2, family=Gamma()) # 0.009

# generalized additive model (GAM) for E 
install.packages("mgcv")
library(mgcv)
gamE <- gam(licor_avg_2$avg.E_2 ~ licor_avg_2$batch + 
s(licor_avg_2$soil_temperature, by=licor_avg_2$batch))
# 7.65e-06 ***; 3.46e-05 ***; 0.0029 **

# model validation for GAM
install.packages("mgcViz")
library(mgcViz)
gamE <- getViz(gamE)
check(gamE) # pattern in 3rd plot; 4th should be a straight line

# GAM for gsw 
gamgsw <- gam(licor_avg_2$avg.gsw_2 ~ licor_avg_2$batch +
s(licor_avg_2$soil_temperature, by=licor_avg_2$batch))
# 3.51e-07 ***; 3.76e-06 ***; 0.000799 ***
gamgsw <- getViz(gamgsw)
check(gamgsw)

# gamma distribution for A/Ci 
gammaA.Ci <- glm(formula = licor_avg_2$avg.A.Ci_2 ~
licor_avg_2$batch + licor_avg_2$soil_temperature, family = Gamma(),
data = licor_avg_2) #0.03847 *
EP <- resid(gammaA.Ci, type = "pearson")
ED <- resid(gammaA.Ci, type = "deviance")
mu <- predict(gammaA.Ci, type = "response")
E_A.Ci <- licor_avg_2$avg.A.Ci_2 - mu
EP2 <- E_A.Ci / sqrt(0.1589045 * mu)
op <- par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(x = mu, y = E_A.Ci, main = "Response residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP, main = "Pearson residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP2, main = "Pearson residuals scaled")
plot(x = mu, y = ED, main = "Deviance residuals")
par(op) 

# individual batches
gammaA.Ci_b1 <- glm(avg.A.Ci_2[licor_avg_2$batch == "1"] ~
licor_avg_2$soil_temperature[licor_avg_2$batch == "1"],
data=licor_avg_2, family=Gamma()) # 0.19

gammaA.Ci_b2 <- glm(avg.A.Ci_2[licor_avg_2$batch == "2"] ~
licor_avg_2$soil_temperature[batch == "2"],
data=licor_avg_2, family=Gamma()) # 0.42

gammaA.Ci_b4 <- glm(avg.A.Ci_2[licor_avg_2$batch == "4"] ~
licor_avg_2$soil_temperature[batch == "4"],
data=licor_avg_2, family=Gamma()) # 0.06

### WATER POTENTIAL
# importing water potential data 
w_pot <- read.csv("data/leafpsi_2023.csv", sep = ";", header = TRUE, dec =",")

# keeping only the days when we also measured water potential
licor_avg_3 <- licor_avg_2[licor_avg_2$date %in% c('04/07/2023','10/07/2023', 
'19/07/2023', '21/07/2023', '25/07/2023', '10/08/2023'), ] 
w_pot_2 <- w_pot[-c(11:15, 29, 31:40), ] 
w_pot_2 <- w_pot_2[order(w_pot_2$TreeID), ]
licor_avg_3 <- licor_avg_3[order(licor_avg_3$tree.id), ]

#adding column for water potential to licor data
licor_avg_3$water_potential <- w_pot_2$psi_avg
licor_avg_3$water_potential <- licor_avg_3$water_potential *(-1)

### WATER POTENTIAL vs SOIL TEMPERATURE: gamma distribution
gamma_wpot <- glm(licor_avg_3$soil_temperature ~ licor_avg_3$water_potential,
data=licor_avg_3, family=Gamma()) # 0.4462
EP <- resid(gamma_wpot, type = "pearson")
ED <- resid(gamma_wpot, type = "deviance")
mu <- predict(gamma_wpot, type = "response")
E_ <- licor_avg_3$soil_temperature - mu
EP2 <- E_ / sqrt(0.7352598 * mu)  
op <- par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(x = mu, y = E_, main = "Response residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP, main = "Pearson residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP2, main = "Pearson residuals scaled")
plot(x = mu, y = ED, main = "Deviance residuals")
par(op)

# GAS EXCHANGE VS WATER POTENTIAL

# gamma distribution for A
gammaA2 <- glm(licor_avg_3$avg.A_2 ~ licor_avg_3$batch +
licor_avg_3$water_potential, data=licor_avg_3, family=Gamma())
summary(gammaA2) # 0.004673 **
EP <- resid(gammaA2, type = "pearson")
ED <- resid(gammaA2, type = "deviance")
mu <- predict(gammaA2, type = "response")
E_ <- licor_avg_3$avg.A_2 - mu
EP2 <- E_ / sqrt(0.2461634 * mu)  
op <- par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(x = mu, y = E_, main = "Response residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP, main = "Pearson residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP2, main = "Pearson residuals scaled")
plot(x = mu, y = ED, main = "Deviance residuals")
par(op)

#individual batches
gammaA2_1 <- glm(licor_avg_3$avg.A_2[licor_avg_3$batch == "1"] ~
licor_avg_3$water_potential[licor_avg_3$batch == "1"], data=licor_avg_3, 
family=Gamma()) # 0.0727 . 

gammaA2_2 <- glm(licor_avg_3$avg.A_2[licor_avg_3$batch == "2"] ~
licor_avg_3$water_potential[licor_avg_3$batch == "2"], data=licor_avg_3, 
family=Gamma()) # 0.22

gammaA2_3 <- glm(licor_avg_3$avg.A_2[licor_avg_3$batch == "4"] ~
licor_avg_3$water_potential[licor_avg_3$batch == "4"], data=licor_avg_3, 
family=Gamma()) # 0.17

# E - significant 
gamEw <- gam(licor_avg_3$avg.E_2 ~ licor_avg_3$batch +
s(licor_avg_3$water_potential, by=licor_avg_3$batch))
# 0.0107 * 0.0611 . 0.2192
gamEw <- getViz(gamEw)
check(gamEw) 

# gsw - significant
gamgsww <- gam(licor_avg_3$avg.gsw_2 ~ licor_avg_3$batch +
s(licor_avg_3$water_potential, by=licor_avg_3$batch))
#0.00632 ** 0.09968 . 0.26244
gamgsww <- getViz(gamgsww)
check(gamgsww) 

# gamma distribution for A/Ci 
gammaA.Ci2 <- glm(licor_avg_3$avg.A.Ci_2 ~ licor_avg_3$batch +
licor_avg_3$water_potential, data=licor_avg_3, 
family=Gamma()) # 0.25387  
EP <- resid(gammaA.Ci2, type = "pearson")
ED <- resid(gammaA.Ci2, type = "deviance")
mu <- predict(gammaA.Ci2, type = "response")
E_ <- licor_avg_3$avg.A.Ci_2 - mu
EP2 <- E_ / sqrt(0.124749 * mu)  
op <- par(mfrow = c(2, 2))
plot(x = mu, y = E_, main = "Response residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP, main = "Pearson residuals")
plot(x = mu, y = EP2, main = "Pearson residuals scaled")
plot(x = mu, y = ED, main = "Deviance residuals") # relabel
par(op)

gammaA.Ci2_1 <- glm(licor_avg_3$avg.A.Ci_2[licor_avg_3$batch == "1"] ~
licor_avg_3$water_potential[licor_avg_3$batch == "1"], data=licor_avg_3,
family=Gamma()) # 0.462

gammaA.Ci2_2 <- glm(licor_avg_3$avg.A.Ci_2[licor_avg_3$batch == "2"] ~
licor_avg_3$water_potential[licor_avg_3$batch == "2"], data=licor_avg_3,
family=Gamma()) # 0.8067  

gammaA.Ci2_3 <- glm(licor_avg_3$avg.A.Ci_2[licor_avg_3$batch == "4"] ~
licor_avg_3$water_potential[licor_avg_3$batch == "4"], data=licor_avg_3,
family=Gamma()) # 0.32
\end{verbatim}

